ly change our experience of geographic knowledge, from the God’s-eye view of the map to the embedded subjectivity of GPS. Likewise, older concerns with geographic truth and objectivity have been upstaged by a new emphasis on simplicity, reliability, and convenience. After the Map shows how this change in geographic perspective is ultimately a transformation of the nature of territory, both social and political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCartographyxHistory. 0aCartographyxMethodology. 0aElectronics in navigationxHistory. 0aGlobal Positioning SystemxHistory. 0aGrids (Cartography) 0aGrids (Cartography). 0aMapsxPolitical aspects. 0aNavigationxHistory. 0aUniversal transverse Mercator projection (Cartography) 0aUniversal transverse Mercator projection (Cartography). 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226339535423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226339535/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles